author: @donnelly5757
text: I think I have what is opposite of imposter syndrome which is inferior complexity. I could be wrong as to the exact definition, but I consistently feel that I may never be good enough to get myself a good job. I tend to perceive myself as inferior to many people. I developed this when I was in the military. I went in at an older age (34) and everyone my age was either an officer or my superior. I began to suffer from depression and anxiety from the social isolation and feelings of loneliness and feelings of not being good enough or far enough in life.  Now having been three year's since I graduated with a master's degree in exercise science, I have yet to work a job that takes any sort of skill. Most the the jobs I have had the past three years are manual labor and retail jobs requiring nothing more than a high-school diploma. I am positive this is contributing to my worsening depression and anxiety along with inferior complexity. I now plan to begin an online master's program in analytics or AI and machine learning, I may end up doing both. I am hoping that by the time I graduate which will be around the age of 47 and having no domain experience, I can land my first data analyst job. I would hope to inspire other people who are in their mid 40s or older that it can be done even if you have worked none other than low-wage, low-skilled jobs. Besides my four years in the military, the most I have made in one year is around 19k. The day I do land a good job, I'll make sure to include some eggplant in my dinner! I thought I'd mention this. Things have been so bad as far as finding a job the past three years, that back in 2018 I filled out an application and sent a resume to work at McDonald's as a crew member! I never heard back! I doubt they have any thing related to eggplant on their menu. They could come up with the McEggplant burger or salad!

Did you try the "escabeche" eggplant?  â€œEscabecheâ€ Eggplant Ingredients   3 large eggplants (about 2.2 lb) 3 tablespoons Himalayan pink salt (or regular granny salt) 2 cups of white vinegar 1 cup of water 1 cup of Olive oil 1/2 teaspoon of black pepper 1/2 tablespoon of Paprika 1/2 tablespoon of chili flakes 1/2 tablespoon of oregano 2 bay leaves 1 cup of sunflower oil, it may be more or less   Marinated "Escabeche" Eggplant by Sigrilina -- This is a great way to preserve eggplants and to infuse them with flavor. Preparation Step 1 Peel the eggplant and cut in 3/8 inch slices. Step 2 Put the eggplant in a bowl and mix thoroughly with the Himalayan pink salt. Let it rest for 30 minutes. Step 3 In a pot mix the vinegar with the water, set aside. Step 4 Rinse the eggplant slices. Step 5 Cook the eggplant in the vinegar-water mixture for 2 or 3 minutes or until they have acquired the hardness of your liking. Check on them often as they tend to be very hard and then to soft quite quickly. Step 6 Drain the eggplant and set aside. Step 7 In a small bowl mix the olive oil with the spices and the bay leaves. Step 8 In a sterilized jar, alternate eggplant and the oil mixture. Remember to put the bay leaves in between. Step 9 When you are done, cover the rest of the jar with sunflower oil until the eggplants are fully covered. Step 10 Before consumption let rest for at least one week in the refrigerator so the eggplants are really infused with the flavor. Step 11 Store in the refrigerator for up to 3 weeks.  source: https://sigrilina.com/marinated-escabeche-eggplant/  You can add it to a sandwich or maybe as an appetizer . Great videos!

Anyway, imposter syndrome is real for me because I moved up the rank too quickly and mostly due to luck (promotion were available at locations that no one wants to relocate to and I was willing to). After a few promotions and finally relocated to a city I want to live in, I definitely feel  that I definitely should not have this job and always paranoid that I will be fired at every single one on one with my boss. So far no bad news yet but it is crazy how the feeling devalue your work. Sometimes I would accomplish something and always think that "anyone could have done that."
